__NOTOC__ [[File:JoekullsarlonBlueBlockOfIce.jpg|right|300px|thumb|Iceberg on [[Jökulsárlón]], Iceland]] '''Blue ice''' occurs when snow falls on a [[glacier]], is compressed, and becomes part of the glacier. Air bubbles are squeezed out and ice crystals enlarge, making the ice appear blue.
Small amounts of regular ice appear to be white because of air bubbles inside them and also because small quantities of water appear to be colourless. In glaciers, the pressure causes the air bubbles to be squeezed out, increasing the density of the created ice. Large quantities of [[color of water|water appear to be blue]], as it absorbs other colours more efficiently than blue. A large piece of compressed ice, or a glacier, similarly appears blue.
The blue color is sometimes wrongly attributed to [[Rayleigh scattering]], which is responsible for the color of the sky. Rather, water ice is blue for the same reason that [[Color of water|large quantities of liquid water are blue]]: it is a result of an [[Overtone band|overtone]] of an oxygen–hydrogen (O−H) [[Rotational-vibrational spectroscopy|bond stretch]] in water, which absorbs light at the red end of the visible spectrum.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.dartmouth.edu/~etrnsfer/water.htm |title= Why Is Water Blue?| first1= Charles L.|last1= Braun |first2=Sergei N.|last2= Smirnov |date=August 1993 | work= [[Journal of Chemical Education|J. Chem. Edu.]], 1993, 70(8), 612| publisher= [[Dartmouth College]]| accessdate=2013-12-22 |quote= }}</ref> In the case of oceans or lakes, some of the light hitting the surface of water is reflected back directly, but most of it penetrates the surface, interacting with its molecules. The water molecule can vibrate in different modes when light hits it. The red, orange, yellow, and green wavelengths of light are absorbed so that the remaining light is composed of the shorter wavelengths of blue and violet. This is the main reason why the [[ocean color|ocean]] is blue. So, water owes its intrinsic blueness to selective absorption in the red part of its visible spectrum. The absorbed photons promote transitions to high overtone and combination states of the nuclear motions of the molecule, i.e. to highly excited vibrations.
An example of blue ice was observed in [[Tasman Glacier]], [[New Zealand]] in January 2011.<ref name= "NZ_Herald_10699700">{{cite web |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/travel/news/article.cfm?c_id=7&objectid=10699700 |title=NZ blue ice sighting an unexpected treat for tourists |last=Harvey |first= Eveline |date=14 January 2011 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |accessdate=21 September 2011}}</ref>
==Antarctic runways== [[File:Antarctic_blueice_hg.png|thumb|right|Blue ice fields in Antarctica]] Blue ice is exposed in areas of the [[Antarctic]] where there is no net addition or subtraction of [[snow]]. That is, any snow that falls in that area is counteracted by [[sublimation (physics)|sublimation]] or other losses.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_RXVBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT256&dq=Blue+ice+is+exposed+in+areas+of+the+Antarctic+where+there+is+no+net+addition+or+subtraction+of+snow&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwih44T0gI_XAhUU6mMKHcjwC0EQ6AEIJjAA#v=onepage&q=Blue%20ice%20is%20exposed%20in%20areas%20of%20the%20Antarctic%20where%20there%20is%20no%20net%20addition%20or%20subtraction%20of%20snow&f=false|title=Antarctic Lakes|last=Laybourn-Parry|first=Johanna|last2=Wadham|first2=Jemma|date=2014-08-14|publisher=OUP Oxford|isbn=9780191649325|language=en}}</ref> These areas have been used as [[runway]]s (e.g. [[Wilkins Runway]], [[Novolazarevskaya]], [[Patriot Hills Base Camp]]) due to their hard surface, which is suitable for [[aircraft]] fitted with wheels rather than [[ski plane|skis]].
