{{Infobox writer | name = Dorothy Hinshaw Patent<!-- include middle initial, if not specified in birth_name --> | image = Dorothy Hinshaw Patent.jpg<!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] --> | alt = | caption = Patent in Hawaii, 2007 | birth_name = Dorothy Hinshaw | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1940|04|30}} | birth_place = [[Rochester, Minnesota]], USA | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|Month DD, YYYY|Month DD, YYYY}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | nationality = American | occupation = Writer and educator | education = BA in biological sciences, Ph.D. in zoology | alma_mater = [[Stanford University]], [[University of California at Berkeley]] | period = | genre = Children's nonfiction | subject = Nature | spouse = [[Greg Patent]] | awards = Washington Post/Children's Book Guild 2004 Nonfiction Award | website = {{URL|dorothyhinshawpatent.com}} }}
'''Dorothy Hinshaw Patent''' (born April 30, 1940)<!--source is Ext link LCCN--> is a teacher and author of over 100 children's nonfiction books.<ref name = "childrensbookguild">{{cite web|title=Washington Post/Children's Book Guild 2004 Nonfiction Award Winner Dorothy Hinshaw Patent|url=http://www.childrensbookguild.org/nonfiction-award/past-winners/2004-winner|work=The Children's Book Guild of Washington, D.C.}}</ref> She lives in [[Missoula, Montana]].<ref name = "scholastic">{{cite web|title=Biography, Dorothy Hinshaw Patent|url=http://www.scholastic.com/teachers/contributor/dorothy-hinshaw-patent|work=Scholastic Teachers}}</ref>
== Awards == She has received numerous awards for her writing.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dorothy Hinshaw Patent|url=http://www.scbwi.org/MemberProfile.aspx?u=43462453828574|work=SCBWI, [[Society of Children's Book Writers and Illustrators]]|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113221933/http://www.scbwi.org/MemberProfile.aspx?u=43462453828574|archivedate=2012-11-13|df=}}</ref> "In 1987, she received the Eva L. Gordon Award from the American Nature Study Society in recognition of her outstanding contribution to science literature for young readers."<ref name = "scholastic"/> She received the Washington Post/Children's Book Guild 2004 Nonfiction Award.<ref name = "childrensbookguild"/>
