Here is a list of the hottest and coldest temperature recorded in Spain.
On July 30, 1876 and August 4, 1881, temperatures of {{convert|51|°C|abbr=on}} and {{convert|50|°C|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Highest Temperature Extremes|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/oa/climate/globalextremes.html|publisher=NOAA Satellite and Information Service|accessdate=2 September 2013}}</ref> were both reported for [[Seville]]: these readings are unreliable, since they were measured under a standard exposure and in poor technical conditions.<ref name="Abc.es">[http://www.abc.es/sociedad/20130617/abci-temperaturas-extremas-registradas-espana-201306171107.html Las temperaturas más extremas de la historia en España]</ref> A temperature of {{convert|48.8|°C|abbr=on}} was also recorded at [[Cazalla de la Sierra]] on August 30, 1926, but is generally not considered valid by international standards,<ref name="Tiempo.com">[http://foro.tiempo.com/records-climaticos-en-espana-temperaturas-t36437.12.html Récords climáticos en España (Temperaturas)]</ref> along with other unofficial readings measured in various locations, probably taken without proper instruments.<ref>[http://www.angelfire.com/ma/maxcrc/old/temp.html Extreme temperatures around the world (Spain)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141108222837/http://www.angelfire.com/ma/maxcrc/old/temp.html |date=2014-11-08 }}</ref> On July 17, 1978, an unconfirmed temperature of {{convert|47.5|°C|abbr=on}} was recorded at Barranco de Masca, [[Tenerife]].<ref name="AEMET1">[http://www.calima.ws/resumen_met/ResMetCan0708.pdf Resumen Meteorológico AEMET - Agosto de 2008]</ref>
