[[Category:Igneous petrology]] [[Category:Volcanic rocks]] [[Category:Intermediate rocks]]

The '''Skagerrak-Centered Large Igneous Province''' ('''SCLIP'''), also known as the '''European-Northwest African Large Igneous Province''' ('''EUNWA'''),<ref>E.g. {{Harvnb|Doblas|Oyarzun|Lopez-Ruiz|Cebriá|1998|loc=Abstract}}; {{Harvnb|Bryan|Ferrari|2013|loc=Fig. 1, p. 1054}}</ref> and '''Jutland LIP''', is a {{Mya|300|million year old}} (Ma) [[large igneous province]] (LIP) centered on what is today the [[Skagerrak]] strait in north-western Europe ({{Coord|57|50|N|9|04|E|display=inline,title}}, paleocoordinates<ref name="Torsvik-etal-p447">{{Harvnb|Torsvik|Smethurst|Burke|Steinberger|2008|loc=Relationship of the Skagerrak LIP eruption site to the deep mantle, pp. 447–448}}</ref> {{Coord|11|N|16|E}} (south of [[Lake Chad]])). It was named by {{Harvnb|Torsvik|Smethurst|Burke|Steinberger|2008}}.
The SCLIP covered an area of at least {{Convert|0.5|e6km2|abbr=on}} and includes the Oslo and Skagerrak [[graben]]s, areas in south-western Sweden, Scotland, northern England, and the central North Sea. The SCLIP erupted at 297±4&nbsp;Ma.<ref>{{Harvnb|Torsvik|Smethurst|Burke|Steinberger|2008|loc=The Skagerrak-Centered Large Igneous Province, pp. 444–445}}</ref> It produced 228,000&nbsp;km² of currently exposed volcanic material that can be found in Skagerrak, the Oslo Fjord, central North Sea, North-east Germany; 14,000&nbsp;km² of [[Sill (geology)|sills]] in Scotland, England, Germany, The Netherlands, and Sweden; and 3,353&nbsp;km total length of [[Dike (geology)|dykes]] in Scotland, Norway, and Sweden.<ref>{{Harvnb|Torsvik|Smethurst|Burke|Steinberger|2008|loc=Fig. 1, p. 445}}</ref> The eruption had a relatively short time span, perhaps less than 4&nbsp;Ma, but magma propagated more than {{Convert|1000|km|abbr=on}} from the plume centre.<ref>{{Harvnb|Torsvik|Smethurst|Burke|Steinberger|2008|loc=Conclusions, p. 451}}</ref>
Plumes derived from a [[superplume]] (or Large Low Shear Velocity Province (LLSVP)) overlay the boundary of the superplume at the [[core-mantle boundary]] (CMB).<ref>{{Harvnb|Torsvik|Smethurst|Burke|Steinberger|2008|loc=Was the SCLIP generated by a mantle plume?, pp. 445-446}}</ref> To test whether the SCLIP met these criteria, Torsvik et al. used a shear-wave [[Tomography|tomographic model]] of the mantle, in which the SCLIP indeed do project down to the margin of the African superplume at the CMB at a depth of 2800&nbsp;km.<ref name="Torsvik-etal-p447" /> A series of LIPs are associated with the African superplume, of which the SCLIP is the oldest: SCLIP (300&nbsp;Ma), [[Bachu Large Igneous Province|Bachu]] (275&nbsp;Ma), [[Emeishan Traps|Emeishan]] (260&nbsp;Ma), [[Siberian Traps|Siberian]] (250&nbsp;Ma), and [[Central Atlantic Magmatic Province|Central Atlantic]] (200&nbsp;Ma). Its possible that these plumes together caused the break-up of [[Pangaea]] and therefore play an important role in the [[supercontinent cycle]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Li|Zhong|2009|loc=Superplume record during the Pangean cycle, pp. 146–147}}</ref>
The SCLIP is associated with the [[Moscovian (Carboniferous)|Moscovian]] and [[Kasimovian]] stages of the [[Carboniferous rainforest collapse]] around 296-310&nbsp;Ma together with the Siberian [[Barguzin-Vitim Large Igneous Province|Barguzin-Vitim LIP]]. <ref>{{Harvnb|Kravchinsky|2012|loc=Table 1, p. 33}}</ref>
